“Longitudinal studies: evidence and potential avenues for research using large-scale cohort data”

The workshop is all about reflecting about some short- and long-term 
consequences of early exposure to policing (or the criminal legal system) across
the life course—throughout the day, we’ll be talking about implications for 
legitimacy judgements and trust in the legal authority, but also for mental 
health, educational performance, criminal offending, among other behavioural 
consequences. The first session, before lunch, will be focused on theory. The 
second session will be about longitudinal data and studies. I thought it could 
be a nice opportunity to discuss some (potentially publicly available) data 
sources, what has already been done with those data, and what can still be 
done—in relation to life-course implications of exposure to policing or contact 
with the criminal legal system. For example, Chuck could present the PHDCN, 
highlight our stuff focused on abusive policing and legal cynicism (or perhaps 
even Rob and Roland’s stuff on arrests), and discuss what else we can do with 
that dataset. David could talk about the ADR data, the benefits and challenges 
of working with administrative data, what has been done and what else can be 
done (I realise that in this case it won’t be about “contact with police”, 
probably more about “contact with the criminal legal system”). Amal could talk 
about the Millennium Cohort Study, what we did for our BJC paper, and what we’re 
doing for our YEF project. This is of course just a suggestion, feel free to 
talk about whatever you want.



